PAX-it SQL Server Setup 3
Preface
Introduction
PAX-it version 6.2 or higher supports various Database System Implementations. The
items described in this manual are designed and implemented for MS SQL Server 7 or
higher.
PAX-it uses database records to store image information such as image title, ID tag
information, and references to video text templates, voicemail, and notepad
messages.
The following manual will aid you in configuring your MS SQL Server database for use with PAX-it
software.
Warning
This document is meant as a guide to help you configure an outside database
management system for use with PAX-it. This guide will instruct you in creating a new,
empty network storage drive within PAX-it using MS SQL Server as the
database manager.
DO NOT: Use this guide if you intend to import an existing PAX-it database in MS
Access to MS SQL Server.
DO NOT: Use this guide if you have an existing PAX-it drive that you wish to update to
use with MS SQL Server database.
Additional help material is available if you plan on upgrading an existing MS Access
Database to MS SQL Server. Although this setup is outside the scope of this
document, it is possible to setup a MS SQL Server database from an existing PAX-it
database. THIS SETUP IS NOT RECOMMENDED.
DISCLAIMER
We provide this guide as a service to our customers and are committed to offering
tools for your benefit. MIS, Inc. is by no mean liable or responsible for your database,
server or data. MIS, Inc. is not responsible for supporting a MS SQL Server
database. MIS, Inc. can be contracted for further assistance. For other tips, hints and
ideas, please visit our website.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 4
I. Initial DB Server and Login Setup
Before PAX-it can store data on the Database Server, you must create and configure a database in
MS SQL Server for PAX-it to use, as well as create username(s) and password(s) with permissions
to access it from an ODBC connection.
Steps for Database Creation in MS SQL Server:
Step 1: - In the Security Properties of your MS SQL Server, please ensure that the
Authentication is set to “SQL Server and Windows Authentication”.
Step 2: - Create a new database named “PAXIT” for your instance of MS SQL Server.
The name MUST be “PAXIT” with NO prefixes or suffixes for PAX-it to operate correctly. If you
have any questions, then please contact PAX-it Technical Support for additional help.
Step 3: - Add at least 2 SQL Logins to your MS SQL Server.
The first login should have PUBLIC, DB_OWNER, DB_DATAREADER and DB_DATAWRITER
privileges to the PAXIT database. This is your Administrative Login for PAX-it.
The second login should have PUBLIC, DB_DATAREADER and DB_DATAWRITER privileges to the
PAXIT database. This is the first client login you will setup for PAX-it.
For each new user added to PAX-it, you will need to create an additional login in MS SQL Server
with the same privileges to the PAXIT database.
WINDOWS LOGINS
It is often desirable to synchronize PAX-it logins with those that already exist in your Windows
Active Directory. Doing so applies all Active Directory passwords, policies and permissions at the
PAX-it level, eliminating the need to manage separate user accounts for PAX-it. To use Windows
accounts, simply add users from your Active Directory in Step 3 above. NOTE: make sure to
change the Default Database in the New-Login dialog to PAXIT when using Windows AD.
It is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED when using Windows Authentication that the FIRST user added
REMAIN SQL-authenticated, which is useful to access PAX-it in the event that unforeseen network
dynamics prevent access to PAX-it via Windows logins. It is also useful as a vendor services
account in any PAX-it support-related matters. All additional users can be Windows authenticated.
Should you desire to manage user access to PAX-it from Active Directory, you may add an AD User
Group as a login to your SQL Server. Assign the same permissions outlined for the 2
nd
login in Step
3 above. Any Windows user added to that AD group will also be granted access to the network
database in PAX-it.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 5
II. Create the Network Share Drive
Step 1: On the File Server, please ensure that the destination folder for the PAX-it
images has been shared with Read / Write / Execute & Modify Privileges for PAX-it
client PC users. For additional information please refer to
FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON THIS STEP, REFER TO THE DOCUMENT PAXIT NETWORK DRIVE AND
FLOATING LICENSE CONFIGURATION
Step 2: On the client machine, right mouse click on Network and left mouse click on
Map Network Drive in the popup menu.
Step 3: In the drive dropdown box, select the un-used drive letter you wish to
associate with the Network Share. For this example, we will use the drive letter ‘P’.
Step 4: In the Folder edit box type in the network path to the shared folder on your
File Server. For example: \\Server\PaxitShare.
Step 5: Please ensure that the option Reconnect at logon is checked, then click OK.
You should now have the “P:” drive available under My Computer associated to your
network share on the File Server.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 6
III. Add Storage Drive to PAX-it
Step 1: Launch PAX-it 2 software.
Step 2: If not yet registered, you will be prompted with a registration screen. Call MIS, Inc. to
permanently register your PAX-it license. Alternatively, you may enter the PAX-it license Serial #
provided with your purchase into the Serial # box of the registration screen and click “Register
Later” to use the license for a limited time without registration.
NOTE: You will eventually need to register your license permanently. Please contact MIS Technical
support at support@paxit.com, or 1-630-279-4000, Ext. 2, and someone will help you.
If not prompted for registration, continue to Step 3.
Step 3: Go to File > Options > Preferences and click on the Storage tab.
Step 4: Click “Add” to add a new storage location within PAX-it.
Drive Name: Enter a friendly name to identify this drive in PAX-it (e.g.
“SQL”, as shown below)
Drive Letter: Enter the drive letter mapped in Section II (e.g. “P’, as
shown below)
Configure Drives Dialog
Step 5: Click “OK”
Step 6: In PAX-it click on the Browse Collection button on the toolbar, and in the drive
selection list, click on the drive name we just created (e.g. “SQL”). Once the cabinet/folder opens,
close the Cabinet View and exit out of PAX-it.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 7
IV. Create an ODBC Connection
Step 1: On the client machine, please ensure that the appropriate client ODBC access
drivers for MS SQL Server are installed. If they are not, first install them and then proceed through
these steps.
Step 2: Run the Windows ODBC Data Source Administrator on the client PC. Select the correct
directory from which to run the application according to your specific operating system
64-bit OS: C:\Windows\SysWOW64\odbcad32.exe
32-bit OS: C:\Windows\System32\odbcad32.exe
or access the same through the Windows Control Panel under Administrative Tools > Data Sources
(ODBC).
Step 3: On the ODBC Data Source Administrator dialog, click on the System DSN tab. Under System
Data Sources, remove any Microsoft Access Driver OTHER THAN that named “PAXIT32_C” from
the list. Do this by highlighting the Name of the data source (e.g. “PAXIT32_X”) and clicking the
Remove button. Click YES to confirm the deletion.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 8
Step 4: Click ADD on the right hand side. On the Create New Data Source dialog
that pops up from the driver list, select the SQL Server Driver you installed/verified
in Step 1.
Click the Add… button in the System DSN tab and select the appropriate SQL driver.
In the setup window:
i. Data Source Name: type in “PAXIT32_X”, where X is the letter of your network drive
ii. Description: type “PAX-it! Image Database”
iii. Server Name: type in the name of your SQL server installation (e.g.
“server\<SQLINSTANCE>”.
iv. Click “Next”
On the second screen…
IF using WINDOWS-Authenticated Logins:
v. Under authentication, select “With Windows NT authentication…”
vi. Click “Next”
vii. Check the box “Change the default database to:” and select PAXIT from the dropdown
list below it
viii. Click Next
ix. Click “Test Data Source…” to confirm that the connection to your database is working
correctly.
x. Click OK and exit Data Source Administrator
IF using SQL-Authenticated Logins:
i. Under authentication, select “With SQL Server authentication…”
ii. Check the box “Connect to SQL Server…”
iii. In the login boxes, enter the username and password of the DBO (administrator) account
in your PAXIT SQL database
iv. Click “Next” twice and click Finish.
v. Click “Test Data Source…” to confirm that the connection to your database is working
correctly.
vi. Click OK and exit Data Source Administrator
vii. In Windows Explorer, browse to the C:\Users\[Username]\AppData\Roaming\MIS\PAXIT
folder, where “[Username]” is the current user logged into the PC.
viii. Double-click on the file “PAXIT.INI”. This will open the file with the default text editor,
such as Notepad.
ix. In the text editor, Search for the text “Database” (no quotation marks)
x. Underneath [Database], create a new line and type exactly LoginDrive=X (where “X”
equals the drive letter of network share mapped in Section II above). The final text will
look like this
[Database]
LoginDrive=X
xi. Click File > Save, then File > Exit to save the changes and close the text editor window.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 9
V. Run the Install Script
Step 1: In Windows Explorer, browse to the C:\PAXIT folder and look for the file
install_db.exe. Run install_db.exe.
Step 2: A dialog titled Install PAX-it! 6.1 Database will be launched. In the edit box
for “Schema:” enter the schema name “PAXIT”. Please ensure that the check box
labeled “Create Log Tables” is checked.
Install PAX-it! 6.1 Database Dialog
Step 3: Click “OK” to run the install script.
Step 4: This will launch the Select Data Source dialog. Click on the Machine Data
Source tab, and scroll down the list to select the DSN connection named “PAXIT32_”
and the letter of the mapped drive to the network share. In this example, the DSN
name is PAXIT32_X. Click “OK” to continue.
Select Data Source Dialog
NOTE: The DSN ‘Type’ MUST be ‘System’. If Type is ‘User’, exit the install_db.exe and remove any
source of the same name from the User DSN tab in the odbcad32.exe administrator tool. Then
continue with this section from the beginning.
PAX-it SQL Server Setup 10
Step 5: Next a login window will appear to connect to the database server. Enter in the
login name and password.
Step 6: The script will run if the login was successful. If no error messages appear,
after the script completes a message box will pop up with the message “Setup
Complete.” Click “OK” to close the message box, and the program will close. If you
receive an error message, PLEASE MAKE NOTE of the listed error message. DO
NOT attempt to run the script again, for additional help with the error message,
contact PAX-it Technical Support (+1 630-279-4000, x2 or support@paxit.com).
AT THIS POINT…
Configurations using WINDOWS LOGINS for access to their SQL network database will be able to
open PAX-it and access the network collection WITHOUT need to log in to PAX-it itself.*
Configurations using SQL Logins requires each user log into PAX-it every time. Please complete
the following Section VI if set up in this fashion, as users must be added to PAX-it software itself
to access the application in this configuration. You must also make sure to have the
“LoginDrive=” text added to the PAXIT.INI (Section IV > Step 4 > SQL Setup > steps vii.-xi.).
*NOTE: Should you want to restrict different users’ permissions within PAX-it software using
Windows Accounts, you must add each user account to the User List section in PAX-it, following
the same steps of Section VI below. You ALSO must edit the PAXIT.INI file as outlined in Section IV.
Create an ODBC Connection, Steps xii-xv of the subsection “If Using SQL-Authenticated Logins”.
The ‘LoginDrive=’ line added in those steps is required to activate the PAX-it User login screen.
